<li id="cite_note-urlThe_Second_Amendment_Under_Fire:_The_Uses_of_History_and_the_Politics_of_Gun_Control-34"><b><a href="#cite_ref-urlThe_Second_Amendment_Under_Fire:_The_Uses_of_History_and_the_Politics_of_Gun_Control_34-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://historymatters.gmu.edu/d/5200" class="external text" title="http://historymatters.gmu.edu/d/5200" rel="nofollow">"The Second Amendment Under Fire: The Uses of History and the Politics of Gun Control - Saul Cornell"</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://historymatters.gmu.edu/d/5200" class="external free" title="http://historymatters.gmu.edu/d/5200" rel="nofollow">http://historymatters.gmu.edu/d/5200</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=The+Second+Amendment+Under+Fire%3A+The+Uses+of+History+and+the+Politics+of+Gun+Control+-+Saul+Cornell&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fhistorymatters.gmu.edu%2Fd%2F5200&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Second_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Saul_Cornell_two_models-35"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Saul_Cornell_two_models_35-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFCornell.2C_Saul2006">Cornell, Saul (2006). <i>A WELL-REGULATED MILITIA — The Founding Fathers and the Origins of Gun Control in America</i>. New York, New York: Oxford University Press. p.&#160;2. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780195147865" class="internal">ISBN 978-0-19-514786-5</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=A+WELL-REGULATED+MILITIA+%26mdash%3B+The+Founding+Fathers+and+the+Origins+of+Gun+Control+in+America&amp;rft.aulast=Cornell%2C+Saul&amp;rft.au=Cornell%2C+Saul&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B2&amp;rft.place=New+York%2C+New+York&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-19-514786-5&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Second_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Saul_Cornell_when_born-36">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Saul_Cornell_when_born_36-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Saul_Cornell_when_born_36-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFCornell.2C_Saul2006">Cornell, Saul (2006). <i>A WELL-REGULATED MILITIA — The Founding Fathers and the Origins of Gun Control in America</i>. New York, New York: Oxford University Press. p.&#160;7. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780195147865" class="internal">ISBN 978-0-19-514786-5</a>.  "The individual rights and collective rights theories were products of later struggles in American history. Individual rights theory was born in the Jacksonian era as a response to America's first efforts at gun control. Collective rights theory emerged slowly at the end of Reconstruction and only crystallized in its modern form in the early twentieth century. The one theory absent from current debate over the Second Amendment is the original civic interpretation. The virtual extinction of the conception was not inevitable but was a product of a long and complex history."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=A+WELL-REGULATED+MILITIA+%26mdash%3B+The+Founding+Fathers+and+the+Origins+of+Gun+Control+in+America&amp;rft.aulast=Cornell%2C+Saul&amp;rft.au=Cornell%2C+Saul&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B7&amp;rft.place=New+York%2C+New+York&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-19-514786-5&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Second_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Konig_civic_duty-37"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Konig_civic_duty_37-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFKonig.2C_David_Thomas">Konig, David Thomas (22.1 (2004)). <a href="http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/lhr/22.1/forum_konig.html" class="external text" title="http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/lhr/22.1/forum_konig.html" rel="nofollow">"The Second Amendment: A Missing Transatlantic Context for the Historical Meaning of "the Right of the People to Keep and Bear Arms""</a>. Law and History Review<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/lhr/22.1/forum_konig.html" class="external free" title="http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/lhr/22.1/forum_konig.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/lhr/22.1/forum_konig.html</a></span>.  "The protection being sought, this shared transatlantic discourse reveals to us, lay in the maintenance of well-regulated militias consisting of able-bodied men bearing their own arms for that purpose. Indeed, to serve in the militia and participate in this civic duty was more than a duty: it was a civic right of a peculiarly eighteenth-century nature unlike either the "individual" or "collective" models argued for today."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=The+Second+Amendment%3A+A+Missing+Transatlantic+Context+for+the+Historical+Meaning+of+%22the+Right+of+the+People+to+Keep+and+Bear+Arms%22&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Konig%2C+David+Thomas&amp;rft.au=Konig%2C+David+Thomas&amp;rft.date=22.1+%282004%29&amp;rft.pub=Law+and+History+Review&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.historycooperative.org%2Fjournals%2Flhr%2F22.1%2Fforum_konig.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Second_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-38"><b><a href="#cite_ref-38" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFKates.2C_Jr.1983">Kates, Jr., Don B. (November 1983). "Handgun Prohibition and the Original Meaning of the Second Amendment". <i>Michigan Law Review</i> (The Michigan Law Review Association) <b>82</b> (2): 204-273.  "In unmistakable individual right terms: As civil rulers, not having their duty to the people duly before them, may attempt to tyrannize, and as the military forces which must be occasionally raised to defend our country, might pervert their power to the injury of their fellow citizens, the people are confirmed by the next article in their right to keep and bear <i>their private arms</i>. (Emphasis in original)".</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Handgun+Prohibition+and+the+Original+Meaning+of+the+Second+Amendment&amp;rft.jtitle=Michigan+Law+Review&amp;rft.aulast=Kates%2C+Jr.&amp;rft.aufirst=Don+B.&amp;rft.au=Kates%2C+Jr.%2C+Don+B.&amp;rft.date=November+1983&amp;rft.volume=82&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.pages=204-273&amp;rft.pub=The+Michigan+Law+Review+Association&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Second_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Sayoko001-39"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Sayoko001_39-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFBlodgett-Ford.2C_Sayoko">Blodgett-Ford, Sayoko (Fall 1995). "The Changing Meaning of the Right to Bear Arms". <i>Seton Hall Constitutional Law Journal</i>: 101.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=The+Changing+Meaning+of+the+Right+to+Bear+Arms&amp;rft.jtitle=Seton+Hall+Constitutional+Law+Journal&amp;rft.aulast=Blodgett-Ford%2C+Sayoko&amp;rft.au=Blodgett-Ford%2C+Sayoko&amp;rft.date=Fall+1995&amp;rft.pages=101&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Second_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-isbn0-8223-3017-2-40"><b><a href="#cite_ref-isbn0-8223-3017-2_40-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFMerkel.2C_William_G..3B_Uviller.2C_H._Richard2002">Merkel, William G.; Uviller, H. Richard (2002). <i>The militia and the right to arms, or, How the second amendment fell silent</i>. Durham, N.C.: Duke University Press. pp.&#160;19, Chapter 9 (pages 212–225). <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0822330172" class="internal">ISBN 0-8223-3017-2</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+militia+and+the+right+to+arms%2C+or%2C+How+the+second+amendment+fell+silent&amp;rft.aulast=Merkel%2C+William+G.%3B+Uviller%2C+H.+Richard&amp;rft.au=Merkel%2C+William+G.%3B+Uviller%2C+H.+Richard&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3B19%2C+Chapter+9+%28pages+212%E2%80%93225%29&amp;rft.place=Durham%2C+N.C.&amp;rft.pub=Duke+University+Press&amp;rft.isbn=0-8223-3017-2&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Second_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
