<li id="cite_note-Saul_Cornell_neither_model-84"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Saul_Cornell_neither_model_84-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFCornell.2C_Saul2006">Cornell, Saul (2006). <i>A WELL-REGULATED MILITIA — The Founding Fathers and the Origins of Gun Control in America</i>. New York, New York: Oxford University Press. p.&#160;6. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780195147865" class="internal">ISBN 978-0-19-514786-5</a>.  "Neither of the two modern theories that have defined public debate over the right to bear arms is faithful to the original understanding of this provision of the Bill of Rights."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=A+WELL-REGULATED+MILITIA+%26mdash%3B+The+Founding+Fathers+and+the+Origins+of+Gun+Control+in+America&amp;rft.aulast=Cornell%2C+Saul&amp;rft.au=Cornell%2C+Saul&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B6&amp;rft.place=New+York%2C+New+York&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-19-514786-5&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Second_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-85"><b><a href="#cite_ref-85" title="">^</a></b> Several public officials, including <a href="/wiki/James_Madison" title="James Madison">James Madison</a> and Supreme Court Justice Joseph Story, retained the confusing practice of referring to each of the ten amendments in the Bill of Rights by the enumeration found in the first draft; had Justice Story followed this practice, he would have described the Second Amendment as the Fourth, but in this case he simply stated the number incorrectly</li>
<li id="cite_note-bliss_v_commonwealth-86">^ <a href="#cite_ref-bliss_v_commonwealth_86-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-bliss_v_commonwealth_86-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <cite><i>Bliss v. Commonwealth</i></cite>, <a href="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs/usr/wbardwel/public/nfalist/bliss_v_commonwealth.txt" class="external text" title="http://www.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs/usr/wbardwel/public/nfalist/bliss_v_commonwealth.txt" rel="nofollow">2 Littell 90</a> (KY 1882).</li>
<li id="cite_note-87"><b><a href="#cite_ref-87" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://courts.ky.gov/NR/rdonlyres/E5470543-A249-4265-8EDD-0C0DDD6A7212/0/2ndKYConstitution.pdf" class="external text" title="http://courts.ky.gov/NR/rdonlyres/E5470543-A249-4265-8EDD-0C0DDD6A7212/0/2ndKYConstitution.pdf" rel="nofollow">Kentucky's Second Constitution (1799)</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-1967hearing-88"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1967hearing_88-0" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=exooAAAAMAAJ&amp;q=%22concealed+weapons+was+violative+of+the+Second+Amendment%22&amp;dq=%22concealed+weapons+was+violative+of+the+Second+Amendment%22&amp;pgis=1" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=exooAAAAMAAJ&amp;q=%22concealed+weapons+was+violative+of+the+Second+Amendment%22&amp;dq=%22concealed+weapons+was+violative+of+the+Second+Amendment%22&amp;pgis=1" rel="nofollow">United States. Anti-Crime Program. Hearings Before Ninetieth Congress, First Session</a>. Washington: U.S. Govt. Print. Off, 1967, p. 246. quote: <i>"...all citizens had the unabridgable right to bear arms for self-protection as well as for militia purposes and that a statute prohibiting the carrying of concealed weapons was violative of the Second Amendment (see Bliss v. Commonwealth, 2 Litt. (Ky) 90, 13 Am. December 251 (1822))...</i></li>
<li id="cite_note-rkba1982-89"><b><a href="#cite_ref-rkba1982_89-0" title="">^</a></b> Right to Keep and Bear Arms, U.S. Senate. 2001 Paladin Press. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1581602545" class="internal">ISBN 1581602545</a>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-90"><b><a href="#cite_ref-90" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFPierce1982">Pierce, Darell R. (1982). "Second Amendment Survey". <i>Northern Kentucky Law Review Second Amendment Symposium: Rights in Conflict in the 1980's</i> <b>10</b> (1).</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Second+Amendment+Survey&amp;rft.jtitle=Northern+Kentucky+Law+Review+Second+Amendment+Symposium%3A+Rights+in+Conflict+in+the+1980%27s&amp;rft.aulast=Pierce&amp;rft.aufirst=Darell+R.&amp;rft.au=Pierce%2C+Darell+R.&amp;rft.date=1982&amp;rft.volume=10&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Second_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-91"><b><a href="#cite_ref-91" title="">^</a></b> Two states, <a href="/wiki/Alaska" title="Alaska">Alaska</a> and <a href="/wiki/Vermont" title="Vermont">Vermont</a>, do not require a permit or license for carrying a concealed weapon to this day, following Kentucky's original position.</li>
