<li id="cite_note-132"><b><a href="#cite_ref-132" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFLinda_Greenhouse2008">Linda Greenhouse (2008-06-27). <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/27/washington/27scotus.html?ei=5124&amp;en=21e70d4578db66b2&amp;ex=1372305600&amp;partner=permalink&amp;exprod=permalink&amp;pagewanted=all" class="external text" title="http://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/27/washington/27scotus.html?ei=5124&amp;en=21e70d4578db66b2&amp;ex=1372305600&amp;partner=permalink&amp;exprod=permalink&amp;pagewanted=all" rel="nofollow">"Justices, Ruling 5-4, Endorse Personal Right to Own Gun"</a>. The New York Times<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/27/washington/27scotus.html?ei=5124&amp;en=21e70d4578db66b2&amp;ex=1372305600&amp;partner=permalink&amp;exprod=permalink&amp;pagewanted=all" class="external free" title="http://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/27/washington/27scotus.html?ei=5124&amp;en=21e70d4578db66b2&amp;ex=1372305600&amp;partner=permalink&amp;exprod=permalink&amp;pagewanted=all" rel="nofollow">http://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/27/washington/27scotus.html?ei=5124&amp;en=21e70d4578db66b2&amp;ex=1372305600&amp;partner=permalink&amp;exprod=permalink&amp;pagewanted=all</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2009-01-05</span>.  "The landmark ruling..."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Justices%2C+Ruling+5-4%2C+Endorse+Personal+Right+to+Own+Gun&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Linda+Greenhouse&amp;rft.au=Linda+Greenhouse&amp;rft.date=2008-06-27&amp;rft.pub=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2008%2F06%2F27%2Fwashington%2F27scotus.html%3Fei%3D5124%26en%3D21e70d4578db66b2%26ex%3D1372305600%26partner%3Dpermalink%26exprod%3Dpermalink%26pagewanted%3Dall&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Second_Amendment_to_the_United_States_Constitution"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-133"><b><a href="#cite_ref-133" title="">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/District_of_Columbia_v._Heller" title="District of Columbia v. Heller">District of Columbia, et al., Petitioners v. Dick Anthony Heller.</a> 554 U.S. ___ (2008), page 13. "Giving 'bear Arms' its idiomatic meaning would cause the protected right to consist of the right to be a soldier or to wage war—an absurdity that no commentator has ever endorsed. See L. Levy, Origins of the Bill of Rights 135 (1999). Worse still, the phrase 'keep and bear Arms' would be incoherent. The word 'Arms' would have two different meanings at once: 'weapons' (as the object of 'keep') and (as the object of 'bear') one-half of an idiom. It would be rather like saying 'He filled and kicked the bucket' to mean 'He filled the bucket and died.' Grotesque."</li>
<li id="cite_note-134"><b><a href="#cite_ref-134" title="">^</a></b> <i>Heller</i>, Opinion of the Court, fn. 23</li>
